out_desc_tool: The Nelson Reading Test, Revised Edition (Nelson, 1962) was utilized to measure pupils' reading comprehension levels. It is designed for use in grades 3 through 9. The test consists of the vocabulary subtest of 100 items to measure vocabulary, and the paragraph comprehension subtest of 75 items to measure reading comprehension, called paragraph test. The paragraph test (forms A and B) was used at the initial and final phases of the study to measure the subjects' reading comprehension levels. The working time for the paragraph test is 20 minutes.

out_desc_tool: Two different sets of Reading Strategy and Comprehension tests, which served as pre- and post-tests, were adopted for assessing students’ abilities in using different reading strategies. Each test consists of eight sections with 47 items. The first six sections, including ‘‘Deletion’’, ‘‘Selection’’, ‘‘Generalization and Construction’’, ‘‘Inferring word meaning’’, ‘‘Error detection’’, and ‘‘Summarization’’ assess students’ ability in applying individual strategy in reading different paragraphs.

Each test consists of eight sections with 47 items. The first six sections, including ‘‘Deletion’’, ‘‘Selection’’, ‘‘Generalization and Construction’’, ‘‘Inferring word meaning’’, ‘‘Error detection’’, and ‘‘Summarization’’ assess students’ ability in applying individual strategy in reading different paragraphs.

out_desc_tool: The test included a story of about 700 words followed by five open-ended questions. Students were asked to analyse the text, to write up the ending of the story, to put the key theme in an abstract, to identify the implications of the story, and to pose and answer self-generated questions. These open-ended tasks involved both reading and writing, and were used to examine the extent to which the children were able to construct meaning based on the text passages. Students were not required to write down correct words or complete sentences, and their responses were evaluated in terms of qualitative understanding and not in terms of how many points they had included.

Students were asked to analyse the text, to write up the ending of the story, to put the key theme in an abstract, to identify the implications of the story, and to pose and answer self-generated questions. These open-ended tasks involved both reading and writing, and were used to examine the extent to which the children were able to construct meaning based on the text passages. Students were not required to write down correct words or complete sentences, and their responses were evaluated in terms of qualitative understanding and not in terms of how many points they had included.

out_desc_tool: Diagnostischer Test Deutsch. The test consists of short texts (150e250 words) followed by questions in multiple-choice format. At each testing-time different texts were used. As most of the questions can be answered by directly taking information from the text, some items were modified in order to require deeper understanding. According to each text 13 questions were presented. The test took 12 min and the students kept the texts in front of them whilst answering the questions.

out_desc_tool: The hierarchy-rating test (Lyytinen & Lehto, 1998) consists of an expository text and 16 text-based statements concerning the text. The subjects are to read the text and then select the two most important statements (topics) and, thereafter six main- point statements. The remaining eight statements are about minor details. This test probes particularly the mental macrostructure of expository texts.
